t1866.text: The world building of the show was one of the greatest aspects of The Good Wife. Because these characters are professionals, they'd routinely work with and against familiar faces & build upon those relationships. Judges, opposing lawyers, process servers, etc would all reappear.pic.twitter.com/uKf8IYXvcg

t1867.text: The show routinely draws upon previous plots, actions, and behaviours to continually inform the forward momentum of its cast. While sometimes characters swam in circles (Eli), they never regressed or were saddled with a status quo.pic.twitter.com/AYjYTf0fqj

t1868.text: While the show was incredibly textured in all the ways we now demand premium TV to be, the show regularly fell victim to the need to fill 22 episodes a year with multi-ep plots that were filler. But it never lost track of the important character and plot building blocks.pic.twitter.com/kICdwbYycY

t1869.text: I particularly love that the show never saddles Alicia with the burden of being a traditional female TV hero. There's episodes where she seeks no-strings sex, she places professional ambition ahead of friendship, and professes to not liking her kids very much. TV never does this.pic.twitter.com/VG9R6rrR2t

t1870.text: I just concluded a rewatch of The Good Wife. It really was one hell of a show. The show may have peaked with its 5th season, but even the season 6/7 episodes were stronger than the shows earliest years. Few shows ever achieve such consistent quality.pic.twitter.com/Mv9REe6QJW
